"Wang S., Yan S., Ma X., Gong J.","Recent advances in capture of carbon dioxide using alkali-metal-based oxides",2011,"Energy and Environmental Science","4","10",,"3805","3819",,,10.1039/c1ee01116b,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80053314792&partnerID=40&md5=11335e67f64140a5aa47e227c124003e","Key Laboratory for Green Chemical Technology, Tianjin University, Ministry of Education, Tianjin 300072, China","Wang, S., Key Laboratory for Green Chemical Technology, Tianjin University, Ministry of Education, Tianjin 300072, China; Yan, S., Key Laboratory for Green Chemical Technology, Tianjin University, Ministry of Education, Tianjin 300072, China; Ma, X., Key Laboratory for Green Chemical Technology, Tianjin University, Ministry of Education, Tianjin 300072, China; Gong, J., Key Laboratory for Green Chemical Technology, Tianjin University, Ministry of Education, Tianjin 300072, China","Carbon dioxide (CO 2) is a major greenhouse gas and makes a significant contribution to global warming and climate change. Thus CO 2 capture and storage (CCS) have attracted worldwide interest from both fundamental and practical research communities. Alkali-metal-based oxides such as alkali-metal oxides, binary oxides, and hydrotalcite-like compounds are promising adsorbents for CO 2 capture because of their relatively high adsorption capacity, low cost, and wide availability. They can also be applied to the adsorption-enhanced reactions involving CO 2. The microstructures (e.g., surface area, porosity, particle size, and dispersion) of these oxides determine the CO 2 adsorption capacity and multicycle stability. This perspective critically assesses and gives an overview of recent developments in the synthesized method, adsorption mechanism, operational conditions, stability, and regenerability of a variety of oxides. Both pros and cons of these oxides are also discussed. Insights are provided into several effective procedures regarding microstructural control of alkali-metal-based oxides, including preparation optimization, modification, stream hydration, etc. © 2011 The Royal Society of Chemistry.",,"Adsorption capacities; Adsorption mechanism; Binary oxides; High adsorption capacity; Hydrotalcite-like compound; Low costs; Microstructural control; Multi-cycle; Operational conditions; Regenerability; Research communities; Surface area; Adsorption; Alkali metal compounds; Alkali metals; Carbon dioxide process; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Metals; Carbon dioxide; adsorption; alkali metal; carbon dioxide; carbon sequestration; global warming; greenhouse gas; hydration; optimization",,,,,,"Stewart, C., Hessami, M.A., (2005) Energy Convers. Manage., 46, p. 403; Hasib-Ur-Rahman, M., Siaj, M., Larachi, F., (2010) Chem. Eng. Process., 49, p. 313; Heintz, Y.J., Sehabiague, L., Morsi, B.I., Jones, K.L., Pennline, H.W., (2008) Energy Fuels, 22, p. 3824; Gale, J., Bachu, S., Bolland, O., Xue, Z., (2007) Int. J. Greenhouse Gas Control, 1, p. 1; Yu, K.M.K., Curcic, I., Gabriel, J., Tsang, S.C.E., (2008) ChemSusChem, 1, p. 893; Wang, W., Wang, S., Ma, X., Gong, J., (2011) Chem. Soc. Rev., , 10.1039/C1CS15008A; MacDowell, N., Florin, N., Buchard, A., Hallett, J., Galindo, A., Jackson, G., Adjiman, C.S., Fennell, P., (2010) Energy Environ. Sci., 3, p. 1645; Choi, S., Drese, J.H., Jones, C.W., (2009) ChemSusChem, 2, p. 796; Wang, Q., Luo, J., Zhong, Z., Borgna, A., (2011) Energy Environ. Sci., 4, p. 42; Phan, A., Doonan, C.J., Uribe-Romo, F.J., Knobler, C.B., O'Keeffe, M., Yaghi, O.M., (2009) Acc. Chem. Res., 43, p. 58; Blamey, J., Anthony, E.J., Wang, J., Fennell, P.S., (2010) Prog. Energy Combust. Sci., 36, p. 260; Yang, H.Q., Xu, Z.H., Fan, M.H., Gupta, R., Slimane, R.B., Bland, A.E., Wright, I., (2008) J. Environ. Sci., 20, p. 14; Hedin, N., Chen, L.J., Laaksonen, A., (2010) Nanoscale, 2, p. 1819; Manovic, V., Anthony, E.J., (2010) Int. J. Environ. Res. Public Health, 7, p. 3129; Scholes, C.A., Smith, K.H., Kentish, S.E., Stevens, G.W., (2